{{short description|Shinto kami}} [[File:Kuninotokotachi.jpg|thumb]] In [[Shinto faith]], '''Kuninotokotachi''' {{Nihongo||国之常立神||extra=''Kuninotokotachi-no-Kami'', in ''[[Kojiki]]''|}} {{Nihongo||国之常立神|1=Kuni-no-Tokotachi|2=ja|3=国之常立神||extra=''Kuninotokotachi-no-Mikoto'', in ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' (no-Mikoto here being an honorific of divinity|}} or '''Kuni-toko-tachi<ref name=":12">{{Cite book |last=Evans Lansing |first=Smith |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to World Mythology |last2=Brown |first2=Nathan Robert |publisher=[[Alpha Books]] |year=2007 |isbn=9781592577644 |location=New York |pages=14}}</ref>''' is one of the two [[kami|God]]s born from "something like a [[Reed bed|reed]] that arose from the soil"<ref>[[Masaki Tsugita]], ''Kojiki'', 1977, {{ISBN|4-06-158207-0}}</ref> when the Earth was [[:en:Chaos (cosmogony)|chaotic]]. In the {{lang|ja-latn|[[Kojiki]]}}, he is the first of the [[Kamiyonanayo|seven generations of Divinities]] born after the [[Kotoamatsukami|first five divinities]] were born at the time of the creation of the Universe. In the {{lang|ja-latn|[[Nihon Shoki]]}}, he is the first of the three divinities born after Heaven and Earth were born out of chaos, and is born from something looking like a reed-shoot growing between heaven and earth.<ref>''Nihongi - Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697 (tr. from the original Chinese and Japanese by W.G. Aston, Charles E. Tuttle Cy. 1990)''</ref> He is known by mythology to reside on top of [[Mount Fuji]] (富士山).
Kuninotokotachi is described as a [[:en:Hitorigami|Hitorigami]] and genderless in {{lang|ja-latn|[[Kojiki]]}}, but is described as a male god in {{lang|ja-latn|Nihon Shoki}}.
[[Yoshida Kanetomo]], the founder of the [[Yoshida Shintō]] sect, identified Kuninotokotachi with [[Ame-no-Minakanushi|Amenominakanushi]] and regarded him as the primordial god of the [[Universe]].
He is a [[:en:Hitorigami|Hitorigami]], or a singular divinity born early in the universe.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2011-05-18 |title=Encyclopedia of Shinto - Home : Concepts of Kami : Hitorigami |url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518151157/http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=10 |archive-date=2011-05-18 |access-date=2023-03-22}}</ref>
He came after [[Ame-no-Tokotachi]] and before {{ill|Toyokumono-no-Mikoto|lt=Toyokumono-no-Mikoto|lt=Toyokumonu|ja|トヨクモノ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyokumonu|qq=}} {{Seven Generations of Kami}}
==See also== *[[Kamiyonanayo]]
==References== {{reflist}}
==External links== *Encyclopedia of Shinto - http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp *Kunitokotachi on the [https://www.historyofjapan.co.uk/wiki/kunitokotachi Japanese History Database].
